{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_manhattan_ver01/data/sn84020355/00279554905/1913123001/1218.xml":{"full_text":"Hie Dkily Independent\nEtut Afternoon E icept Sundat\n4\nW. W.Booher,Editor and Proprietor\n\nSubscription Kates\nOne Year by Mall Jb.00\nSix Montba by Mail IB.00\nFor any period under six months. ?S cents per\nmonth. Delivered by carrier in Elko at ?5 cents\nper month or 25 cents per week- All subscrip\ntions pavable In advance.\nj.- w..?\nTttk-- Weekey Independent\nSubscription Rates*\nYoar?......v.. m* 14-00\nSix Months 12.50\nPublished every Friday and sent to any address\nat the above rates, uavable in advance.\nEntered at the Elko postoBle lor transmission\n?.trough tbc mails as second-class matter. .J.\nWILSON NOTTO BLAME\nThe business depression which is\nsweeping the country at this time\nis being used effectively and dia\nbolically by politicians and anti\nadministration newspapers to stir\nup anti-Wilson sentiment.\n'Tis true, the country is just now\n4\nin the throes of re-adjustment. But\nPresident Wilson did not create the\nsituation. The blame lies on the\nshoulders of those responsible for\nthe sixteen years of riotous, crook\ned high %nance which antedated\n1913. Republi.an measures, be\nginning with the late Mark Hanna's\nascendency in Washington in 1896\nand continuing up to and including\nthe last days of the Taft adminis\nratien in 1912, are responsible.\nBecause it so happens that Presi\ndent Wilson occupies the White\nHouse at the moment is only a for\ntuitous circumstance. He is the\neffect, not the cause.\nIt is unfair to assume that this\ncountry is suffering at this moment\nfrom the acts of the present chief\nexecutive as it would be to say that\nthe paralysis which has just been\nvisited upon the ..decrepit old man\nnext door has been caused by the\nfood he has eaten this year at his\nnew hotel. The causes and the\nfoundation of his paralysis of this\nt, ygar happened and were laid years\nf ago hy either heredity or wrong\nhabits and his habits of this year\ncannqt be distorted into even a\nsuperinducing cause for his malady.\nHad Mr. Taft succeeded himself,\nthe uresent business depression\nmight have been headed off for a\nshort period, but eventually there\nwould have been a cataclysm that\nwould have engulfed the nation.\nWe are now suffering for the\nsins of our forbears.\nSome of our suffering, indeed is\nvicarious, because posterity shall\nto an extent be beneficiary. But\nsurely nor.e of this generation has\ncause to lament the fact that a\nhalt has been called on the 10 year\nold Juggernaut that, under the\nguise of Prosperity, was gradually\nenslaving the nation.\nThe era of financial license and\nlibidinousnes? has abruptly ended\nand the country is suffering from\nthe shock. But it is certainly bet\nter that the end should be now and\nthat the new reckonng should com\nmence this year than that the in\nevitable be postponed.? New York\nMining Age.\nBlack Friday.\nBlaok Ftjday in the financial his\ntory of the United States was Septem\nber 24, 1660, when Oould and other\n?peculators ran the price of gold up\nto 362%, catching a great many per\nsona in a corner and causing a panto.\nIn British .^nancial history Black Fri\nday wan May 11, 1866, on which day\nthe commercial panlo caused by the\nfailure of Overend, Gurney Ca,\nlimited, reached Its height\nO\nMtzpah.\nTho word Mtzpah or Mlzpeb, la He\nbrow. and means \"Watch Tower.\" Fpr\nexample, see Genesis 31:49, where wo\nread, \"And Mlapah, for he said, the\nLord watch between me and theo,\nwhen we are absent one frpm anoth\ner.\" For additional light on the sub\nject you may look at JudgeB 10:17;\n11,11; 20:1. Also I. Samuel, 7:6; 10:17.\ni\nW Hi.\nKithor Way Wstild Do.\n'It woeld be fttce ft everything one\ntouched turned to gold, wouldn't it?\"\nasked the'dreatifer. \"Yes; or If ovory\none one touched turned over gold,\"\nsuggested the deadbeat?Buffalo Ex\nLaw Regulating Fashions,\nlu 1639 the ~?Mieral court of Massa\nchusetts pass; a law that \"No gar\nment ihall be made with short sleeves;\nand such as have garments with short\nsleeves shall not wear them unless\nthey cover the arm to the wrist. And\nhereafter no person whatever shall\nmake an* garment for women with\nsleeves more than half an ell wide\n(twenty-two and a half inches).\" If\nlaws regulating fashions were passed j\ntoday, how many women would be\nfiued ror law-breaking?\nPure Gold.\nPure gold Is considered as divisible\nIn respect to purity into U4 parts, each\ncalled a carat, (or karat), an Qld term\nfor one-twenty-fourth of an ounce,\nTroy. Hence the phrase IS carat fine\nmeans that 18 twenty-fourths is pure\ngold, and the remainder an alloy mate\nrial. Ordinary gold chains and jew\nelry are usually only 14 carat tine,\nbut wedding rings are \"2 carats fine.\nEnough for Him.\nTwo negroes were cnce matched for\na boxing contest. Finally one began\nscoring heavily, and the ether went to\nhis corner at the cud of the round bad\nly beaten. He failed to respond when\nthe bell rang. \"Coma on berth. niggali,\ndis am a fight to a finish.\" challenged\nthe more lively of the pair. The bat\ntered one simply sat in his corner\nhead down, dejected. \"Yes, an* 1'se\nfinished,\" he grunted.\nTo Die in the L.-*t Oitch.\nThe saying to Die 1 b Last Ditch,\nmay be attributed to William of Or\nange. When Buckingham urged the\nI inevitable destruction which hung\nover the united provi r s and asked\nhim whether he did net see that\nthe commonwealth was ruined: 'Thero\nis one certain meant,\" replied the\nprince, \"by which 1 c::i be sure never\nto see my country's ruin.?i will die ia\nthe Jast ditch.\"\nMasterful 3luo-Eyed Women.\nBlue-eyed beauties are known for\ntheir self-control, coldness, raster it y\n\"and precision. They are c arc and\nsuspicious, and demand the continu\nous homage of those about them.\nMoreover, they are domineering and\nmasterful, and wherever pc sible will\nbe found to rule the roost.\nCato, on Buying a Farm.\nWhen you have decided tc, buy a\nfarm, he careful not to buy rashly;\ndo not spare your visits, and be not\ncontent with a sin.-'e lour of inspec\ntion. Give heed to tlie appearance of\nthe neighborhood: p HotirL-hing coun\ntry should show its prokp rby.?Cato.\nT rumped.\n\"I wish I had never learned to play\ncards!\" exclaimed :t man who had\nbeen unfortunate at the game. \"You\nmean you wish you had learned, don't\nyou?\" was his wife's sarcastic re\njoinder.\nSoftening Granite Slabs,\nis been observed that, under\nconditions which have not\nplained, granite will warp lilco\nv.i A slab set in a wall has been\nunder observation In-Switzerland, and\na perceptible distortion has made Ik\n?elf apparent.?Harper's Weekly.\nMoon!i:.!-t.\nThe light of the i .on is .he time\nfrom new moon to full moon, and the\ndark of the moon is from full moon to\nnew moon, or throughout the waning\nperiod.\nNothing in It.\nAn advertiser calls his patent wash\ning machine \"The ,Indies' Delight.\"\nNow, If there in anything about wash\ning tbjit delights the Indies, v/e should\nilko to know what if in. Thty are any\nthing but delighted on a warning day.\nReal Test of Sympathy.\nAnybody can sympathise with tho*\nsufferings of a friend, but it requires a\nvery line nature?it. recpj: >s, in fact\nthe nature of a true in.! idealist?to\nsympathize with a i:i nd's success.?\nOscar Wilde.\nOutput of Copper.\nAmerican copper mines turned out\n218,679,183 pounds of copper in 1912,\nnearly 2,000,000. lesr. than in 1911, but\nthe value was $8,502,182 greater.\nDaughter Was Curious.\nInvited out to dinner, mother stood\nbefore the mirror, and, having mado 1\nher yellow locks a trifle yellower, she 1\nproceeded to apply tho pencil to her\neyebrows. The little daughter stood\nby and wondered. Finally she naked::\n\"Mother, what are you writing on\nyour face for?\"\nWhy?\n\"But don't you want to give me a\nkiss, Manollta \"No, nol My grand\nfather nays you'vo got tho tongue ot\na viper!\"?Blanco y Negro (Madrid).\nWhat Would Newspapers Do?\nIf It were not for our mistakes,\nife would be protty monotonous.-*\n'odge.\n\nUse an-Eraser. i\nFor removing dirty marks from\nlight-colored cloth, use n piece of In-\ndla rubber eraser; the spots will die- j\naopem immediately, I\n0\n9\nPOSTCARD SENT NEWLY WEDS\nHighly Decorated Remembrance l?\nInscribed With Advice\nFrom Sender.\nE>enrer.?A wooden postcard nearly\ntwo feet long aud more than half a\nfoot wide and highly decorated ^lth\ninstructions to p?lvly married couples\nwas handed to E. C. Bennett, clerk at j\nthe Kaisei-hoff hotel, by the letter car\nrier when making his usual mail de\nlivery.\nIt was addressed to .dr. and Mrs.\nRoy D. Leo of Pueblo, who were here\non their honeymoon. The couple had\ndeparted, however, before the card ar\nrived. Clerk Bennett tried to put it in\nthe mail box and it wouldn't go. Then\nhe hung it up over his desk. That\ncaused so many people to make use\nless remarks that he shoved it uuder\nthe counter.\nThen some one told liim he was In\nterfering with the United States mails,\nso he took it out agaiu and handed it\nto the telephone operator, who wrote\nanother address on it aud forwarded\nit ixfter the happy couple.\nOne motto said: \"May all the\ntroubles be little ones.\" Another said:\n\"Be good to one another.\" Another\ncard asked the clerk, iii the event he\ncould not deliver the postcard, to re\nturn tp the couple addressed at Rose\nlawn cemetery, Pueblo, Colo., as that\nwould undoubtedly be their stopping\nplace in the end.\nThe card had thirty-four stamps on\nit aud numerous pictures of hearts,\ncupids and other designs which con\nveyed the impression that the parties\nadtli-essc-d were in a blissful state of\nmind.\nMASTER JAILED, DOG STRIKES\nw\nSearching for His Owner, Hector Dis\nappears and Police Are Asked\nto Look for Hint.\nMinneapolis.?This is a story of a\ndog tiiat went on a hunger strike. It\nis also a story of a man the dog adopt\ned. showing his faithfulness and set\nting the whole police department on a\nhunt for the dog.\nHector is the dog and Frank Trez\nwick of St. Cloud, Minu., is the man.\nThe man took a drop too much and\nwas snagged into the East Side police\nstation. The dog accompanied him'and'\nwhen his friend disappeared cellward\nHector set up a howl that kept the po\nlicemen awake. Frank was fed in his\ncell aud loud was offered Hector in\nLieut. J. Quealey's otTice. but Ilector\nwould not eat. He would only howl.\nWhen Frank was fined and It looked\nas if lie would have to spend a few\ndays in the workhouse, arrangements\nwere made to have Hector cared for at\nthe pound, but Frank paid his fine and\nasked for Hector.\nTlio dog's howling has ceased, but\nthe rolicemen were surprised when\nthey discovered that Ilector was ndt\nin the room where he had been lock\ned. He had wriggled between narrow\nbars and had gone to look for Frank.\nNow ti?? police have been instruct\ned to find Hector and restore Frauk\nto him.\nGREAT WAR CHIEF STARVING\nDire Straits of Matabcle W.-rrlor in\nEnglapd Through Inability to\nWork.\nLondon.?Loben Lobengula, cldosl\neon of Lobengula, the famous Mata\nbole warrior, is living In dire stralta\nof poverty in Phillips street, Whitlane,\nSal ford. He is afflicted with conaump\ntion and Is no longer able to work,\nand his wife and children exist on\ncharity.\nAt the end of tlio last Mntabele war\nin 1806, the tribe was scattered, and\nLobengula came over to England with\na Savage South Africa show. For\nthree years be t<x?rcd this country,\nand then got an engagement in'a Man\nchester' pftntomime. In 1881 ho mar\nried an Irish woman, and In the fol\nlowing year he went to work in a pit\nat Pendleton. Since he settled at\nSafford he has lived the life of a col\nlier. He waB quick to pick up work\nIn the mine, and became proficient in\nhis lob.\nThe Rev. 8. O. Bees, vicar of the\nparish in which Lobengula lives, says\ntho circumstances in which the son of\nthe African chief had been reduced\nsuggested a very lamentable disregard\nof English tradition of generosity to\nvanquished adversaries.\nCoitsc t-rappe.\nTo one pint of cold strong coffee\n(one-half cup ground coffee to one\nquart water) add one scant cup of\nRUgr.r, stir until dissolved, then pro\nceed as usual. After the mixture has\nbeen scraped from the sides of the\ncylinder the second time, or when\nhalt' frozen, servo In frappe glasses\nwith a star of whipped cream upon\nthe t*?p#of tho fruppo In each glass.\ncook ics.\nOne cupful of butter, two cupfuls of\nsugar, three eggs, half a tcaspoonful of\nbakfr.g powder, oiiq even toaxpoonful\nof nutmeg, half a tcaspoonful of cloves\nand flour for a soft dough. Begin with\ntwo cupfuls and ndd carefully that you\nmay not make them too Btlff. Cream\nbutter and sugar, add yolks of eggs,\nspice) one cupful of flour with baking\npowder, tho whipped w^tes and tho\nrest of the flour. Roll Into a sheet a\nquarter of an Inch thl> k, cut Into\nrounds and bake In a good oven.\nThese cookies ought to bo of the soft\nrarlety yon keep them wrnpped Ut\ni cloth In a tin box arid will not let\n.hem dry out. t\nDUE TO DEFECTIVE. FLUES\nEnormous Financial Loss by Fire Is\nCredited to Carelessness In\nThis Respect.\nThe campaign against the enormous\npreventable Are waste of the counti*y\nhas naturally led to a study of the\nprincipal hazards and those which can\nmost easily be avoided. Hazard.- are\ndivided broadly into two classes?phy\nsical and moral?the physical hazards\nbeing inherent in the risk Itself and in\nIts surroundings, while tho moral haz\nard arises from personal factors.\nPhysical hazards may be subdivided\nInto external and internal. This ex\nternal hazards include lightning, con\nflagrations; sparks, boulires ar.d ex- I\nposure losses. To this cause are due\n28 per cent, ef all losses both as to\nnumber and value. The internal haz\nards are much more numcious and\nmay be subdivided into iivu classes.\nThese are: Spontaneous combustion, j\nthe hazards due to the operation of\nmachinery, the hazards incident to\nprocesses, those due to the various\nsystems and kinds of apparatus used\nfor heating and lighting, while the\nfifth division includes all those not al\nready classified.\nThe various processes of heating\nwhich usually include the actual use\nof fire are responsible for more losses\nthan any other cau. c, aud under this\nclass it should be noted that defective\nflues are responsible for twice as\nI many fires as any other physical or\nknown moral hazards, and for a great\ner property loss than any other cause.\nStatistics show that 13 per cent, of\nthe total number of fireB can be attrib\nuted to defective flues, with a prop- j\nerty loss of over $12,000,000 annually.\nElectricity is responsible for the larg\ner nroporticn of the losses due to il\nlumination, although rot for tho larg\nest number of sueh losses.?Insurance\nPost.\nEasy Economy.\nA propos of tho 50 cent increase in\nthe price of coal. Miss Evangeline\nBooth, of the Salvalidn army, said\nat the New York headquarters:\n\"And tills increase, of course, will\nbear hardest on the poor. The poor,\nbuying their coal by the bucket or by\nthe ouarter-ton, will pay this increase\na dozen times over. And the rich,\nbuying their coal by the carload, will\n(lodge by means of discounts the iix\ncre^se altogether.\n\"There was a lot ef truth in the re\nmark of the poor, harassed. East Side\nhousewife whose hnsband complain\ned:\n'I wish you would be more econom\nical, Mary. Look at the boss' wife,\nhow economical she is!'\"\n\"'Yes,' Mary replied, 'it's easy\nenough for the bo<=3' wife to be eco\nnomical. She's got plenty to be eco\nnomical with!\"'\nHow to Clean Marble Told.\nScraping luarble which has been\nblackened or turned green by air and\ndamp is dangerous to the design;\nwhatever precautions may be taken,\nthe work is always scratched more or\nless, and it is impossible to cleanse\nthe carved parts without breaking the\nsculpture or causing incongruities be\ntween the designs in relief a; d those\nwhich are sculptured. Soiled a. Mcics,\nwhioh have not been tarnished oy ex\nposture to the open air. may be\ncleansed bj potash water, then wash\nthem in pure water and finish with\nwater containing a dash of hydro\nchloric acid. Soap, and water Is often\nsufficient, spread on with a brush, and\nintroduced into the sculpture parts by\na somewhat stiff pencil.?Construction\nNews.\nBarr Bars Sloveno.\nCapt. Parr of the Carmnnla, who\ndistinguished liimer.lf in tho Voltumo\nrescue work, is a strict but jdst disci\nplinarian.\nOf Capt. Barr, who insists on spot\nless neatness always, they tell a story\nIn shipping circles.\nA very dirty young diver, it appears,\nwan boasting in an hotel smoking\nroom about the dangers of his call\ning.\n\"Yetf,\" said tho young man, ns he re\nlighted tho stub of his cigar?\"yes,\nyou sailors, Capt. Barr, think you lead\na dangerous life, but I, let mo tell you,\nI carry my life In my hands.\"\n\"Oh, I see,\" said Capt. Barr, \"and\nthat's why you never wash them, eh?\nfor fear you'll drown yourself.\"\nHad 'Em All.\nIn Chicago thoy aver that thfc Is a\ntruo story.\nAt ono of tho \"universal providers,\"\nor department stores, a shoppor asked\na floorwalker where she might find\ntho \"Brussels counter.\"\n\"Carpets, sproute, or point lace,\nma'am?\" was the walker's query.\nDocked the Cats' Talla.\nMonasteries and convents seem nat\nurally to befriend cats. Vhon Sir\nHenry Layard was at Mt. Athos In\n1845 ho noticed the number of \"huge,\nfat, ovorfed catB\" kept by the monks.\nOno peculiarity struck hlrn. Tho cats\nwere almost ns tailless as If thoy wore\n'Manx, but evidently by artificial\nmeans. \"Op. asking for nn explana\ntion of It I was Informed by th?\nmonks tlmt as their meals wore\nserved to them on trays placed, Turk\nish fashion, on low stools, round which\nsquatted thoso who ate, tho cats, who\nwere constant guests at dinner and\nbreakfast, wero In '.ho habit of sweep\ning off the viands and the wine\nglasses with their tails, which were\nconsequently docked.\"\n\nVISITS BIG PRINTING OFFICE\nI\nMre. Woodrow Wilson Gets Watchman\ninto Trouble by Unexpected Call\nat Print Shop.\nMrs. Woodrow Wilson, wjfo of\nj President Wilson, lias been doing a\ngood deal of slumming in Washington\ni ever since she has been here. She\nhas visited ail of tlie wretched alleys,\nand they are really not ver^ numer\nous; all the Uimbled-down buildings,\nand we have quite a lot of those, and\nshe is now making the.rounds of the\nj departments to see wherein the con\nditions of the clerks can be bettered.\nThe other day she wandered up to\nthe government printing office with\nuomo friends to mako a personal in\nspection of the conditions uuOerwhich\nwomen are working in tl'At building.\nMrs. Wilson always request* that it\nbe not made known who she is, and\nfurthermore she insists upon visiting\nthese places unexpectedly, so that\nj thero can be no sweeping and dusting\nbeforehand.\nAt the government printing ofllce\nshe was received by llenry E. Terry,\nj one ol the watchmen, and to him she\ngave ho\" orders not to let her identity\nbe known, then asked him to accom\npany her around the building.. Mrs.\nWilson declined to let Publ'c Printer\ni Ford know that she was there, and\nso tliyi or watchman could do noth\ning mil tremble in bis shoes and\ntramp around over the great* building\nwith the first lady of the land,\" who\nwas appearing incognito. Mr. Terry\nwas nearly scared to death, and as\nsoon as she was out of the otlice?\nand she got out without anybody find\nI ing out she had been there?Terry\nreported to Public Printer Ford that\nthe president's wife had been there.\nVery naturally he was enraged that\nthe wife of the president of the\nI United States should have been re\nceived in the government printing\noffice just as anybody else was re\nceived who wandered in oh the\nstreets. Public Printer Ford did not\nk\nbelieve that this comported with the\ndignity of the department or himself,\nand as Watchman Terry had eom\nmitted a grave breach of the rules\nFord Immediately dismissed him.\nOf course Watchman Terry was\nsomewhat up in the air. He wanted\ntc bo entirely loyal to the government\nprinter, and yet he had a dim notion\nthat the wife of the president of the\nUni^tui.States ranked everybody, and\nbetween tho two he was about to lose\nout, when he had the forethought of\nappealing to Senator Lane of Oregon.\nSenator Lane immediately visited the\nWhite House, told what had happened\nand implored Mrs. Wilson to use her\nbest efforts to have Watchman Terry\nreinstated. This Mrs. Wilson pioceed\ned to do, and Terry is again on the\njob, a wiser if not sadder man. It will\ntake more than the wife of the presi\ndent of tiu: United States to mako\nTerry breaa another rule of the gov\nernment printing oflico. The Wilsons\nare not at all ostentatious, and in\ntheir efforts to be just common people\nare continually getting somebody into\ntrouble.\n\n\nUnusual Stomach.\n\"Chew your food, Doris, before you j\ncwallow it; your stomach hasn't teeth\nto chew with.\" \"Mino hu3.v I swal-\nlowed two last summer.\"?Life.\nurve Fruit to Mayor of London.\nAn ancient city privilege was wit-J\nnessed at London a few days ago,!\nwhen tho lord mayor, Sir David Bur-'\nfictt, was presented by the printers\nwith a fine collection of luscious fruit.\nThe gift marked tho continuance of a\ncustom which has oxisted for many\nyears and is a survival of the days\nwhen the lord mayor was en 'tied to\nsample all tho fruit that came into\nthe city. All tho fruit presented re\ncently was grown in England, and\nmost of it ca:no from Kent. Perfectly\nshaped pineapples,. velvety peaches,\napples, pears and melons, and, indeed,\nalmost overy variety of fruit England\ncan produce wore to bo seen In the\noverflowing cornucopia and three\n'large baskets, decorated with enrnr\ntionR and blue silk ribbon in whic -j\nthe gift was contained.\nNot so Classy.\nFirst Old Friend?\"Hullo, old chap,\nhow uro you?\" .Second O. F.?\"First\nclass; how are you?\" F. O. F,'?\n\"Steerage.\"?Harvard Lampoon.\nTO KENT?An lea H.use in\ngo id order. Capacity, 25 tons.\n1'iqairejjof L. E. Morgan. Advt.\nPostal.Telegraph Cable Company.\nFastest in the' world. Day mess\nages an night letters everywhere.\nMoney!\" telegraphed to all the world\n\nCables all foreign countries\nSee the new lin of Christmas\nand New Year iPi.st Cards, also a\nI\nfull shipmen ot new popular\nwhich al,c acceptable ChrisflKis\ngifts now on sale at News Stand in\nPostal Telegraph Uffi e where you\nget all the latest magazines and\nd.dly papers.?Advt.\nThe Howell Jewelry company has\nmoved to their new store, next\ndoor to the Post Office, where they\nhnv.' a complete line of holiday\ngoods, jewelry and everything in\nhat line fiom a baby's ring a\ndiamond. Mrs. Howell, ihe com\nany's optician, will be foundxat\nj the Hi *e of tne company ready t\n1 str ighten eyes, fit glass s or do\nany work in her lino. Advt.\nUtilization of Watte Cork.\nj Waste cork 1b used tor a variety ot\npurposes I.ifo buoys are filled with\nBcraps ol cork; ilnolemn, n variety of\nfloor-cUv made from linseed oil\nand pulverized cork paper, a material\nused for packing bottlea, Is made by\ncoating strong paper with an udheBlve\nmixture and sprinkling powdered cork\nover it; cork is sometimes used In\nj place of wood shaving* In the prepara\ntion of vinegar; and illuminating gas\nhas been made from cork waste by dis\ntillation in a retort.\nf i\nBRADLEY\nOPERA HOUSE\nTO-NIGflf\n/lReelsPictures/|\nSpecial feature in l\\vo parts,\n\"Erckcn Threads United* V\n?Essanay.\nFeaturing Richard C. Travers.\nPathe's Weekly\n\"Smashing Time\"\n?Lubin?Comedy.\nADMISSION 10 2.*\nPictures Start 7 30\nREX THEAfRE\nPROGRAM TO-NIGF f\n\"Makers and Spenders\"\nDrama?Reliance.\n\"Flotsam\"\n?Drama?K. B.\n?'Lovie The Lifesaver\"\nDrama?Thanhouser.\nSocial dance Saturday night at 9:30\nP. M. TICKETS 50 cents.\nRex Theatre Orchestra.\nShow starts at 7:30 sharp.\nTHANKSGIVING SPECIALS\n1\nFruit and Vegetables as Follows:\nCelery, Spinach, Lettuce, St Beans, Wax Beans, Ar\ntichokes, Tomatoes, Brusscl Sprouts, Peppers,\nRhubarb, Parsley, Grapes, Cranberries,\nGrape Fruit, Strawberries, Raspberries,\nGranges, Bananas, Apples, Mince f ,Q\nMeat, Turkeys, Gccs6, Oysters.\n\nWe also have the the Savory Self Basting 'Roasters,\n'something that should be in every kitchen.\nCarving Sets of every description.\n\nW. T. SMITH COMFANY\nA","height":"32096","width":"23704"}}
